## Migration: Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why this breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006). `ThreadAbortException` is never raised, and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone. You must switch to cooperative cancellation.

### Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` in Stop | Blocking wait | `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne` or graceful join |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock waits
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work (replaces ThreadAbortException catch)
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we just continue to loop exit naturally
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread didn't stop — it's stuck in uncooperative code.
                // Log a warning. You cannot force-kill it in modern .NET.
                // If this is a real risk, move work to a child process.
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key changes to `GetNextItem`

If `GetNextItem` blocks (e.g., on a queue), it **must** accept and respect the token:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks forever
}

// After (.NET 8) — wakes up on cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact | Fix |
|---------|--------|-----|
| Not passing token to blocking calls (`Take`, `Sleep`, `WaitOne`) | `Stop()` hangs — the thread never wakes up | Pass `token` to every blocking API or use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` instead of `Thread.Sleep` |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it silently | Loop never exits | Only catch it for cleanup; let the `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` condition handle exit |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Timer/callback leaks | Implement `IDisposable`, dispose `_cts` |
| Expecting instant stop after `Cancel()` | Cancellation is cooperative — only fires at checkpoints | Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations inside `ProcessItem` |
| Using `Thread.Join()` without timeout | Deadlock if thread is stuck | Always use `Join(TimeSpan)` and handle the timeout case |
| Truly uncooperative code (native calls, third-party libs) | Cannot be cancelled cooperatively | Move to a child **process** and use `Process.Kill()` as last resort |

### If you need the `ResetAbort` semantics (skip item, keep processing)

The original code used `ResetAbort` to keep the thread alive after an abort. The cooperative equivalent is simply continuing the loop:

```csharp
catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    RollbackCurrentTransaction();
    break; // exit loop — cancellation means "stop"
}
```

If you need per-item cancellation (abort one item but keep processing), use a **linked token**:

```csharp
while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
    try
    {
        var item = GetNextItem(token);
        ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Only the item was cancelled, not the whole processor
        RollbackCurrentTransaction();
        continue; // process next item
    }
}
```

### Summary

The paradigm shift: **you can no longer inject an exception into another thread**. The worker must voluntarily check for cancellation. Pass `CancellationToken` through the entire call chain, check it in loops, and pass it to all blocking APIs.
